All of this is great! As we already have a construction of a projective resolution, would not it be easier to prove the horseshoe lemma as follows, given a short exact sequence `0 ⟶ X₁ ⟶ X₂ ⟶ X₃ ⟶ 0` and projective resolution of `X₁` and `X₃`, construct a projective resolution of `X₂` which fits in between? This may be slightly easier than reconstructing everything. The only data which would have to be produced is the differential on the "naive" coproduct of the two resolutions.

I just tried to define the differential $P_{n + 1} \oplus Q_{n + 1} \to P_n \oplus Q_n$ where $P$ is a projective resolution for $X_1$ and $Q$ for $X_3$ but couldn't get it to work, one of the commutativity I can't prove. I documented the failed attempt at `Horseshoe'.lean.failed_attempt`

Feel free to re-use the draft code at https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/compare/master...horseshoe-jriou where I construct the relevant part of the middle differential `δ`, the middle complex is `Qcomplex`, and it fits into a short complex `shortComplex` of chain complexes, and I have defined the augmentation `shortComplexε`, so that I think all the compatibilities should be ok. Then, we have to show that `shortComplex` is short exact, which is easy because degreewise we have a splitting. Finally, more importantly, in order to show that the `Qcomplex` is a (projective) resolution, you may use lemmas which are not yet in #12638 but shall soon be PRed (see https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/jriou_localization/Mathlib/Algebra/Homology/HomologySequenceLemmas.lean#L270 )
